1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The Italian game is a trendy alternative to the
classical Spanish Game (or Ruy Lopez) . Theory has developed massively over
the past years, but there is room for new trends still. One of them is:} d6 $5
{This modest move is a flexible way of meeting the Italian Game (or Giuoco
Piano) . Optically, it looks like a solid but slightly passive move, aiming
for Philidor or Pirc structures after d2-d4, ...exd4. This is the way Steinitz
used to treat several open games. Much later, Geller played a similar setup
against the Four Knight's Defence. I will reveal that I have also played a few
games according to the philosophy described above. Still, when analyzing the
repertoire suggested in this case, my intention was different. Black's last
move is solid because it consolidates e5 in anticipation of d2-d4. It does not
need to be passive, though! Black is ready to adapt his reaction according to
White's next move. As a rule, he would play a move contributing to the fight
for the centre and not give it up with ...exd4. Curiously, against White's
main continuations, Black reacts each time differently! Before moving on, just
a few words about the two main lines in the Italian Game, explaining why
players started looking for alternatives for Black.} (3... Nf6 {is an
ambitious move, with several drawbacks concerning the repertoire suggested
here.} 4. d3 ({First of all, Black has to know what to do after} 4. Ng5 {
, forcing him to sacrifice a pawn. The practice has shown that Black gets
enough compensation, but the theory has developed abruptly over the past years
and one needs to analyze and remember relatively long lines.}) 4... Be7 (4...
h6 {followed by ...g7-g6 is interesting, but a bit slow.}) 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 d6
7. a4 {As mentioned later, this is an important tabyia. White has some chances
to retain some light pressure, but Black is in no danger. Once again, the
problem is that theory is very well developed. Our repertoire offers a
shortcut to this system in Line 8.}) (3... Bc5 {can be met in many ways,
including a quick c2-c3 followed by d2-d4 and the Evans Gambit. However, the
main psychological problem may arise in the Giuoco Pianissimo:} 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3
{The structure is almost symmetrical, but White's play maybe just a bit more
flexible. The knight on c6 stands slightly in the way of the c-pawn, and the
b1-knight has slightly better maneuvering possibilities. Plus, there is a lot
of theory here, too.}) (3... Be7 {is not a good move order, since after} 4. d4
{White retains an edge (more about it later}) 4. O-O {This is the most
flexible and promising move. Displaying early ambitions in the centre would
play into Black's hands, allowing him to prove the merits of his third move.} (
{In the event of} 4. d4 {Black can take advantage of the fact that e5 is
defended to play the developing and counter-attacking} Nf6 $1 {[%emt 0:00:01]
Line} 5. d5 (5. Nc3 {runs into} Bg4 {[%emt 0:00:02] with effective pressure on
the white centre - Line}) 5... Ne7 {[%emt 0:00:03] transposes to some Modern
or King's Indian Defence, in a favourable version for Black - Line}) (4. c3 {
is adequately answered with the slightly exotic, but entirely viable} f5 $1 {
! as in line Line 4. The position after} 5. exf5 Bxf5 {is examined in Line 5.})
4... Be7 {Since he needs to count with Ng5, Black needs to choose this
developing move order. In Line 6 I have examined a few minor continuations} 5.
a4 {This is the most challenging continuation, examined in Line 8. White
offers a transposition to the main line after 3... Nf6, but Black can avoid it.
Having delayed ...Nf6, he can use the extra tempo to question the stability of
the white bishop on c4.} (5. d4 {is examined in Line 7. Once again, this is a
bit premature for similar reasons as before.} Nf6 {We will see that there are
some concrete differences with respect with Line 1, especially in the case
White plays dxe5. All these subtleties offer us an image of the flexibility
and universality of this system.}) *

