1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 d6 4. d4 {The same reaction as to 3...Be7 is less
effective now. With the e5-pawn well-defended, Black can strive for
counterplay in the centre.} Nf6 $1 {The most active continuation, not fearing
any ghosts.} (4... Be7 {would transpose to 3...Be7 4.d4 d6, leaving Black with
the more passive side of a symmetrical structure.} 5. dxe5 dxe5 ({In Line 6,
after the insertion of 0-0 and ...Nf6, Black can take with the knight on e5,
but here} 5... Nxe5 $2 {loses to} 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Qh5 $18) 6. Qxd8+ Bxd8 7. Nc3
Nf6 8. Be3) (4... exd4 {is a positional concession.} 5. Nxd4 Nf6 (5... g6 {
has a consistent drawback.} 6. O-O Bg7 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Nc3 $14 {Unfortunately,
the most active and natural way of developing runs into a typical refutation.}
Nf6 $6 9. e5 dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bxf7 $14) 6. Nc3 Be7 7. O-O O-O {We are
again back into a line arising after 3...Be7. Black's position is playable,
but a bit passive.}) (4... Bg4 {is premature with the king's knight on g8:} 5.
h3 $1 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 {The pawn on f7 is hanging now.} Nf6 7. d5 $16) 5. Ng5 {
This is an important reaction to 3...Nf6, but the insertion of the moves ...
d7-d6 and d2-d4 make things simpler for Black.} (5. dxe5 {is too simplistic.
With the bishop on e7 still, ready to go to c5 or b4, Black does not face any
special problems.} dxe5 6. Qxd8+ (6. Qe2 {does not offer White any chances for
an advantage in the resulting symmetrical structure.} Bd6 7. O-O h6 8. Rd1 Qe7
9. Be3 O-O $11 {Petrucci,R-Velasquez,M Merida 1997 (½-½, 53)}) 6... Nxd8 7.
Nc3 (7. Nxe5 {leads to an inoffensive pawn exchange.} Bd6 8. Nf3 Nxe4 9. O-O
Be6 $5 $146 {=}) 7... Bd6 8. Bg5 {An ambitious way of developing.} (8. O-O {
leads to simpler play.} Be6 9. Bb3 a6 10. h3 O-O 11. Bg5 Bxb3 12. axb3 Nd7 13.
Rad1 Ne6 14. Be3 Rfc8 {Black has regrouped harmoniously.} 15. Nd2 f6 16. g3 b5
$11 {The position is balanced and White's attempts to take over the initiative
will expose his centre.} 17. f4 exf4 18. gxf4 Re8 19. f5 Bc5 20. Rde1 Nd4 $15 {
Bortnyk,M (2473) -Paravyan,D (2647) Chess.com INT 2020 (½-½, 71)}) 8... c6 9.
O-O-O Bc7 10. Bh4 {White intends to increase the pressure on e5.} (10. Bxf6
gxf6 11. Nh4 {is not dangerous for Black. Two bishops, a good regrouping and a
mobile queenside structure compensate for the kingside weaknesses.} b5 12. Be2
Nb7 13. Nf5 Be6 $11 {possibly followed by ...a7-a5.}) 10... b5 11. Bb3 Nb7 12.
Bg3 Nd7 (12... Bg4 $1 {threatening to spoil White's structure would have been
stronger. The exchange sacrifice} 13. Bxe5 Bxf3 14. Bxc7 Bxd1 15. Rxd1 {
does not yield White full compensation.} O-O 16. f3 Rfc8 17. Bg3 Rd8 $15) 13.
Ne2 Nbc5 14. Ned4 {One of the ideas behind White's previous regrouping.} f6 (
14... Bb7 $5) 15. Nxc6 {White has won a pawn, but if he cannot activate the
bishop on g3, Black will have excellent compensation.} Nxb3+ 16. axb3 (16. cxb3
Bb7 17. Ncd4 $2 exd4 18. Bxc7 Rc8 $19) 16... Nc5 $1 $146 ({The careless} 16...
Bb7 $2 {ran into} 17. Ncd4 $16 {Aronian,L (2782) -Artemiev,V (2699) chess24.
com INT 2021 (1-0, 40)}) 17. Ncd4 Bd7 {Everything is defended now.} 18. Rhe1
Ba5 19. b4 (19. c3 b4 20. Nf5 Nxb3+ 21. Kc2 Ba4 $19) 19... Bxb4 20. c3 Rc8 21.
Nf5 Bxf5 22. exf5 Ba5 23. b4 Bxb4 24. cxb4 Nd3+ 25. Kd2 Nxe1 26. Nxe1 O-O $13 {
With mutual chances and approximate material equality.}) (5. Nc3 {is examined
in Line 2.}) ({For} 5. d5 {, see Line 3.}) 5... d5 $1 {A paradoxical situation.
Black is a tempo down concerning 3...Nf6 4.Ng5 d5, but the exposed pawn on d4
allows him to achieve counterplay easily.} 6. exd5 (6. dxe5 Bg4 {The most
active.} (6... Nxe5 7. Bxd5 Bb4+ 8. c3 Bc5 $44 {leaves White a bit hanging.})
7. Be2 (7. f3 {leaves the knight isolated on g5.} dxc4 $1 8. exf6 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1
gxf6 10. fxg4 O-O-O+ 11. Nd2 fxg5 $15) 7... Bxe2 8. Qxe2 Nxe4 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10.
Qxe4 {The most principled.} (10. Bf4 $6 {is too passive.} Qd5 11. O-O Nd4 12.
Qd1 O-O-O $17 {Duda,J (2729) -Artemiev,V (2709) Tornelo INT 2021 (½-½, 32)})
10... Qd4 11. Qxd4 Nxd4 12. Kd1 O-O-O {Black's advance in development yields
him adequate compensation for the pawn.} 13. Nd2 Bc5 14. c3 Nc6 15. f4 Be3 16.
Rf1 g5 $44 17. fxg5 (17. g3 gxf4 18. gxf4 Rhg8 $17) 17... Nxe5 18. Re1 (18. Kc2
Nd3 19. Nb3 Nxc1 20. Nxc1 Rd2+ 21. Kb3 Bxg5 $15) 18... Bxd2 19. Bxd2 Nc4 20.
Re2 h6 21. gxh6 Rxh6 {Threatening ... Rhd6.} 22. Kc2 Nxd2 23. Rxd2 Rxd2+ 24.
Kxd2 Rxh2 $11) 6... Nxd4 7. d6 (7. c3 {leads to more quiet play.} Nf5 8. d6
Nxd6 9. Nxf7 Qd7 $1 (9... Nxf7 $2 10. Bxf7+ $18) 10. Nxd6+ {Illescas Cordoba,M
(2525) -Hebden,M (2455) France 1989 (0-1, 38)} Bxd6 11. O-O (11. Qe2 Qg4 $5 $11
) 11... Qf5 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Nxd7 14. Be3 O-O-O 15. Nd2 Bc5 $11 {Black's
activity and the weakness on d3 compensate for the Isolani on e5.}) 7... Qxd6
8. Bxf7+ (8. Nxf7 $2 {runs into} Qc6 $1 {with a decisive double attack.} 9. b3
Qxg2 10. Rf1 Bg4 $19 {Bain,M (1557) -Piecuch,P (1332) FICGS email 2013 (0-1,
14)}) 8... Ke7 {Black has lost the right to castle and the king stands funny
in the bishop's way. However, White's pieces are hanging and his development
is poor.} 9. Bb3 {The only move out of the trouble.} (9. c3 $2 h6 10. cxd4 hxg5
11. Bb3 {Sanikidze,T (2439) -Blagojevic,T (2260) Terme Catez 2022 (1-0, 89)}
exd4 12. Bxg5 (12. Qe2+ Be6 13. Bxg5 Re8 14. Bxe6 Kd8 $19) 12... Qe5+ 13. Qe2
Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Bf5 $17 {followed by ...c7-c5 and ...Kd7. Black's majority is
by far more dangerous than White's.}) (9. Bc4 $2 Qc6 $19) 9... Nxb3 10. axb3 h6
11. Nf3 (11. Qxd6+ cxd6 $15) 11... Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Bg4 $11 *

