1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 d6 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3 {This is aimed to be more
consistent than 5.Ng5, but offers Black a tempo for increasing his pressure on
d4.} Bg4 6. d5 {White finds it difficult to maintain the tension.} (6. Be3 {
allows Black to weaken White's dark squares.} exd4 7. Bxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bxf3 9.
gxf3 g6 10. O-O-O Bg7 11. e5 {Otherwise, Black will reach a perfect blockade
on dark squares with ...Nh5 and ...Be5.} Nh5 $1 $146 {The right square for the
knight.} 12. Qd5 O-O 13. exd6 Bxc3 $5 14. bxc3 cxd6 15. Qxd6 Qa5 $1 $44 {
White's extra pawn does not count and his structure is weak and the king
vulnerable.}) (6. dxe5 {is inoffensive.} dxe5 7. Bg5 (7. Qxd8+ Rxd8 {followed
by ...Bb4 yields Black easy play, too.}) 7... Bb4 $11 {Mogirzan,M (1813)
-Abrashkin,B (2407) Chess.com INT 2020 (0-1, 19)}) (6. Bb5 {looks like the
main alternative to the main move. However, it looks as if White played a
Steinitz Ruy Lopez with a tempo down, due to the time wasted by his bishop in
reaching b5.} Nd7 $5 $146 {Renewing the threat on d4 by unpinning the
c6-knight.} 7. dxe5 (7. d5 Nd4 8. Be2 Nxe2 9. Qxe2 Be7 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Bg5
$11) (7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 Nxe5 $15) 7... dxe5 $1 (7... Ndxe5 8. Be3 $16 {
With the white light-squared bishop on board, the exchange on f3 is not
disturbing. White is better developed and has good attacking chances,
especially if Black allows the opening of the g-file.}) 8. Bxc6 {The only
consistent move. Otherwise, Black could play ...Nd4.} bxc6 9. h3 Be6 10. Qe2 f6
11. O-O Bb4 12. Bd2 a5 13. b3 Qe7 14. Na4 Nb6 $11 {The kingside looks perfect
while on the queenside, Black's regrouping absolves him of any problems
connected with the pawn weaknesses.}) 6... Nd4 7. Be3 {Playing for rapid
development.} (7. Be2 {is less ambitious.} Nxe2 8. Qxe2 c6 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3
cxd5 11. exd5 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. a4 Rc8 14. a5 a6 15. Be3 Nd7 16. Qe2 f5 $15 {
Belenkaya,D (2293) -Jovanovic,Z (2517) Chess.com INT 2020 (0-1, 31)}) 7... a6
$5 $146 {This apparently modest move defends b5, allowing Black to maintaining
the tension. The last move implies a pawn sacrifice actually.} ({The point is
that} 7... g6 $2 {runs into} 8. Bxd4 exd4 9. Bb5+ $1 $18) (7... Nxf3+ 8. gxf3
Bd7 {is playable, but White has chances for retaining some pressure.} 9. Qd2 g6
10. O-O-O Bg7 11. Be2 $14 {/= Gonzalez,B (2317) -Souza Neves,A (2094) Rio de
Janeiro 2011 (1-0, 30)}) 8. Bxd4 (8. h3 {just offers Black a tempo for free.}
Bxf3 9. gxf3 g6 10. f4 b5 {The move ...a7-a6 can be useful in many ways, as we
can see.}) 8... exd4 9. Qxd4 Bxf3 10. gxf3 g6 {Black has excellent
compensation for the pawn, due to his stronger bishop and the weakness of the
dark squares in White's camp.} 11. e5 (11. O-O-O Bg7 12. Qe3 Nh5 13. Ne2 b5 14.
Bd3 O-O $44) 11... dxe5 12. Qxe5+ Be7 {The most ambitious approach is keeping
the queens, of course.} ({Even} 12... Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Bxe7 $44 {looks OK for
Black..}) 13. O-O-O O-O $44 {Black's compensation is beyond doubt.} *

