1. e4 e5 {It is useful to mention the following move orders, typical for
completely different openings, which may lead to either approximate or perfect
transposition.} (1... g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. c3 (4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Be2
e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 {This is the famous Mar del Plata attack initial
tabyia. The extremely rare and rather pointless} 9. Bd3 $6 {transposes to the
main line.}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nf6 {is the more popular move order.} 5. Bd3 O-O 6.
O-O Nc6 {If White intends to answer ...e7-e5 with d4-d5, he needs to waste a
tempo on a move like} 7. h3 {or 7.Re1.} e5 8. d5 Ne7 9. c4) 5. Bd3 e5 6. d5
Nce7 7. c4 Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O {transposing below.}) ({The move order
starting with} 1... d6 {may be relevant for the line without ...g7-g6 below.}
2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 Nc6 5. d5 Ne7 6. c4 Ng6 7. Nf3 {transposing to the
line mentioned in the comments to 6...g6 below.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 d6 4. d4
Nf6 5. d5 {With the bishop on c4, this looks a bit weird, but since White has
not played c2-c3, the bishop retreat to d3 followed by c2-c4 is likely to
transpose to the move orders mentioned above.} Ne7 6. Bd3 (6. Nc3 {does not
make sense. After} g6 7. O-O Bg7 {hite does not have a coherent queenside plan.
}) 6... g6 (6... Ng6 {is also playable.} 7. c4 (7. h4 Nf4 {may lead to
entertaining play.} 8. Bxf4 exf4 9. Qd2 Nh5 10. Nc3 g6 11. e5 {White does his
best to fight against the blockade on dark squares.} Bg7 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. e6
fxe6 14. dxe6 Bxb5 15. Nxb5 Bxb2 16. Rb1 Bf6 $13 {White has certain
compensation for the pawn, but Black should not be too worried.}) 7... Bg4 8.
h3 (8. g3 {restricting the knight on g6} Qc8 $5 $146 {stabilizes the bishop on
g4.} 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Be2 {Play transposed to Anand,V (2635) -Timman,J (2630)
Linares 1991 (1-0, 28) where Black played ...Qc8 one move later than in our
line.} c6 $5 $146 11. Be3 Bd8 {Black has a harmonious regrouping. The bishop
could go to b6 or a5.} 12. dxc6 Qxc6 13. h3 Be6 $11) (8. O-O {Allows Black to
carry out a typical regrouping.} Be7 9. h3 Bd7 10. Nc3 h6 11. Be3 Nh7 12. b4 a5
13. a3 axb4 14. axb4 Rxa1 15. Qxa1 Bg5 $11) 8... Bxf3 {This exchange usually
favours White in the structure with a blocked centre, but here the black
knights are ready to display effective activity.} 9. Qxf3 Nh4 10. Qg3 Nh5 11.
Qg4 Nf4 12. Bf1 (12. Bxf4 $2 h5 $1 {Taking on f4 at once is also playable, but
this intermediate move yields Black an advantage.} 13. Qg5 exf4 {The point is
that the white queen is hanging now. The pawn on f4 is taboo, of course, due
to ...Nxg2+.} 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Rg1 g5 $17) 12... f5 (12... h5 13. Qg3 Be7 $13
{may be a bit simpler.} 14. Qxg7 $2 Nfg6 $19 {trapping the queen next, with
either ...Bf6 or ...Bf8.}) 13. Qg3 {Teterev,V (2518) -Chashchev,S (2310)
Sukhumi 2006 (1-0, 30)} (13. exf5 h5 14. Qg3 Be7 15. Qxg7 Bf6 16. Qg3 Qd7 17.
Nc3 Qxf5 18. Bd2 O-O-O $44) 13... Be7 14. Qxg7 (14. Nc3 O-O $15) 14... Nhg6 {
With the pawn on h7 instead of h5, this is the best knight retreat; otherwise,
the queen could escape to h6.} 15. Bxf4 Bf8 16. Qxh8 Nxh8 $15) 7. c4 Bg7 8. Nc3
O-O 9. O-O {He has reached the practically non-existing Mar del Plata attack
with 9.Bd3.} (9. h3 {is an attempt at transposing to some Makogonov attack
version after a later g2-g4. In principle, the fact that Black had committed
himself to ...Nc6-e7 before White got castled may cause problems in the King's
Indian, but here Black is a tempo up.} a5 $5 $146 {A subtle way of
anticipating White's intentions.} 10. Be3 (10. g4 {neglects the development.}
c6 11. Be3 (11. a4 Nd7 12. Be3 Nc5 {yields Black stability on dark squares.})
11... b5 $1 12. dxc6 bxc4 13. Bxc4 Nxc6 $132) 10... Nh5 {This is an improved
version of the usually played 9...Nh5. In the main line, Black gets the tempo .
..a7-a5 for free.} 11. g4 Nf4 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. Qd2 a4 $1 14. a3 (14. Rc1 f5
15. exf5 gxf5 16. g5 Ng6 17. h4 Ne5 $132) (14. Qxf4 a3 15. Qd2 axb2 16. Qxb2 f5
$19) 14... c6 15. Qxf4 b5 16. cxb5 cxb5 17. O-O (17. Bxb5 Rb8 $17) (17. Nxb5
Ba6 $17) 17... f5 18. exf5 gxf5 $44 19. g5 $6 Ng6 20. Qb4 f4 $36) 9... Nd7 (
9... a5 {is another possible move order.} 10. Rb1 Nd7 11. a3 f5 12. b4 h6 13.
Re1 f4 14. Nb5 b6 15. Nd2 g5 16. Nb3 a4 (16... f3 $6 17. g3 {Nguyen,A (2567)
-Rahman,Z (2535) Kolkata 2004 (1-0, 33) allowed White to consolidate.}) 17. Nd2
Ng6 18. Be2 Nf6 $132) 10. Be3 (10. b4 a5 11. bxa5 (11. Ba3 axb4 12. Bxb4 b6 13.
a4 Nb8 {Planning to stabilize the queenside with ...Na6.} 14. a5 c5 $1 {
winning a pawn for debatable compensation.} 15. dxc6 Nbxc6) 11... Nc5 12. a4
Rxa5 $13) 10... f5 11. Ng5 Nf6 12. f3 Bh6 $1 $146 (12... Kh8 {is not a bad
move, but Black does not need to be over cautious.} 13. c5 {Macovei,A (2455)
-Jumabayev,R (2637) Chess.com INT 2021 (0-1, 41)} h6 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Ne6 Bxe6
16. dxe6 d5 17. Bc5 Rc8 18. Ba3 dxe4 19. fxe4 Qb6+ 20. Kh1 Qxe6 21. exf5 gxf5
22. Bxe7 Qxe7 23. Bxf5 Rcd8 24. Qe2 e4 $132 25. Nxe4 Rde8 26. Rae1 Qb4 27. Rf3
Nxe4 28. Bxe4 Qxb2 $11) 13. exf5 (13. Bd2 f4 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. dxe6 Kh8 16. Qb3
b6 $13) 13... Nxf5 (13... gxf5 14. Bd2 f4 $6 15. Ne6 Bxe6 16. dxe6 {leaves
Black a bit weak on the light squares.}) 14. Bd2 Qe7 15. g4 $5 (15. Qc1 Nh5 16.
g3 c5 $11) 15... Nh5 $1 (15... Nd4 {allows White to consolidate with} 16. h4
$14) 16. Nce4 (16. Nge4 Ne3 17. Qe1 Nf4 18. Bxe3 Nxd3 19. Qe2 Bxe3+ 20. Qxe3
Nf4 $11) 16... Nf4 17. Bxf4 exf4 18. gxf5 Bxg5 19. fxg6 Bh3 20. gxh7+ Kh8 $13 {
with excellent compensation for the pawns.} *

