1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 ({Just for fun, I will mention that the initial idea of
the Philidor defence was} 2... d6 3. d4 f5 $2 {as played among others by
Morphy. In our main line, the advance of the f-pawn is more to the point.}) 3.
Bc4 ({I would mention the following Ruy Lopez line:} 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. c3
f5 {The so-called Siesta variation.} 6. exf5 Bxf5 {White's bishop is better
placed in this line than in the Italian variation, pinning the knight and not
being exposed to ...d6-d5.} 7. O-O Bd3 8. Re1 Be7 9. Bc2 Bxc2 10. Qxc2 Nf6 11.
d4 $14) 3... d6 4. c3 {This move requires from Black certain accuracy.} f5 $5 {
In my (possibly subjective) opinion, the only adequate answer. Black takes
advantage of the fact that White has delayed both his castle and the
occupation of the centre. We can call the last move an improved version of the
original Philidor's idea. Black uses as many pawns as possible to fight for
the centre. The relative weakness of the a2-g8 diagonal is not dangerous, as
White is not too well developed.} (4... Be7 $6 {allows White to prove that his
