8. Nc3 Nf6 $15) (6. a4 Nxc4 7. dxc4 {Das,A (2482) -Shalamberidze,A (2333)
Albena 2012 (½-½, 76)} f5 8. Nc3 Nf6 $13) (6. Nc3 Nxc4 7. dxc4 f5 $5 $146 8.
c5 Nf6 9. cxd6 cxd6 10. exf5 Bxf5 11. Bg5 Qd7 12. Qd2 O-O 13. Rad1 Rad8 $11 14.
Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 Bg4 16. Qd3 Be7 $11) 6... Nxc4 7. dxc4 g5 $5 {We can see
this idea a lot in different openings.} (7... f5 {is also good, of course.}) 8.
c5 g4 9. cxd6 Qxd6 10. Qxd6 cxd6 11. Nfd2 f5 12. Nc3 Nf6 $11 {Teo,W (2195) -Wu,
W (2476) Singapore 2006 (½-½, 47)}) (5. Re1 g5 $5 $146 {If Black intends to
keep the game within independent paths with respect to the 3...Nf6 4.d3 Be7
line is the move to be played.} (5... Nf6 {is likely to transpose to the
aforementioned line.}) 6. d4 {The principled reaction. "An attack on the wing
should be answered in the centre!"} (6. d3 g4 7. Nfd2 h5 8. Nc3 Bg5 $11) 6...
g4 7. d5 Na5 8. Nfd2 Nxc4 9. Nxc4 f5 {Black has good counterplay.} 10. exf5
Bxf5 11. Na5 (11. Nc3 Qd7 12. Ne3 h5 13. Nxf5 Qxf5 14. Ne4 Nf6 $11) 11... Qd7
12. c4 (12. Nxb7 Qb5 $19 {traps the knight.}) 12... h5 $5 13. Nxb7 g3 $1 {
A typical way of speeding up the pawn attack. In Sicilian lines with opposite
castles, White frequently plays g5-g6 with the reserve pawn on h4, while Black
has ...b4-b3 followed by ...a5-a4.} 14. fxg3 (14. hxg3 h4 $36 15. gxh4 $2 Bxh4
16. Nc3 Qh7 $19) 14... h4 $36 15. gxh4 $2 Bxh4 16. Rf1 (16. g3 Bxg3 17. hxg3
Qh7 $19) 16... Nf6 17. Nc3 Rg8 18. Qe2 Qh7 $19) (5. c3 {is examined in Line 7.}
) ({For} 5. a4 {see Line 8.}) 5... Nf6 6. d5 {Maintaining the tension or
exchanging on e5 are inoffensive. The main move is familiar to us, having more
of practical value. Objectively, Black should have no problems, but he needs
to know what he is doing. Unlike in the previous lines with ...g7-g6, the
knight does not have the e7-square for retreating.} (6. Nc3 {runs into} Bg4 7.
dxe5 (7. d5 Nd4 8. Be2 Nxe2+ 9. Qxe2 O-O 10. h3 Bd7 $11) 7... Bxf3 $1 {Now is
a good moment for this exchange. Black would choose a way of taking on e5
depending on White's answer} 8. Qxf3 (8. gxf3 dxe5 $11) 8... Nxe5 9. Qe2 Nxc4
10. Qxc4 O-O 11. Bf4 {The position is typical for the Steinitz Defence in Ruy
Lopez. After exchanging a few minor pieces, Black can organize his counterplay
more easily.} Re8 $1 $146 {It is strange that this typical move is a novelty.}
12. Rad1 (12. e5 dxe5 13. Bxe5 c6 14. Rad1 Qb6 $11) 12... Bf8 13. Rfe1 (13. e5
Nh5 14. exd6 Nxf4 15. d7 Qg5 16. g3 Red8 17. Qxf4 Qxf4 18. gxf4 Bd6 $11) 13...
c6 14. e5 d5 15. Qb3 Qc7 $11) (6. dxe5 {is offensive.} Nxe5 $1 {With the
knight on f6, this is possible and quite good. Black clears the path for the
