9. f3 (9. Nc3 c6 10. a4 Be7 11. Be3 Nd7 12. Rfd1 {½-½ Doric, D (2464)
-Drazic,S (2467) Zagreb 2011} a5 $11) (9. f4 Nxe4 10. fxe5 O-O 11. Re1 Nc5 12.
Be3 Be7 13. Nc3 {Stankovic,M (2375) -Govedarica,R (2389) Kraljevo 2011 (0-1,
52)} c6 $11 {followed by ...Be6.}) 9... c6 10. Be3 Nd7 (10... Bb6 11. Kf2 Ke7
12. Nd2 Ne8 13. Bb3 Bxe3+ 14. Kxe3 Nd6 $11 {Vayntrub,D (2101) -De Guzman,R 
(2483) San Francisco 2005 (0-1, 52)}) (10... b5 11. Bb3 Bb6 12. Kf2 {Novotny,M
(2337) -Simacek,P (2462) Czech Republic 2012 (0-1, 37)} Ke7 13. a4 b4 {
Planning ...Ba6.} 14. Bc4 Ne8 $1 {! Preparing to fight against the blockade on
light squares.} 15. Nd2 Nd6 $11) 11. Nd2 Bb6 12. Kf2 Ke7 13. b4 a5 $11 {
Chizhikov,V (2229) -Belyakov,B (2511) Minsk 2015 (½-½, 67)}) 6... Nb8 {
The fact that the knight had to retreat to the initial square is a small
achievement for White. However, he is not in time to consolidate, since e4 is
hanging and the bishop is slightly misplaced on c4.} 7. Nc3 {The attempt to
build up a King's Indian centre with} (7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. c4 {runs into} Nc5 {
SInce the pawn on e4 is hanging, White is not in time to keep his bishop with
Bc2.} 9. Nc3 Nxd3 {This exchange solves Black's space problems.} 10. Qxd3 O-O
11. Nd2 Nh5 12. g3 Bh3 $1 (12... g6 {is sound but a bit slow.} 13. b4 f5 $132 {
Anand,V (2786) -Ivanchuk,V (2738) Leuven 2017 (½-½, 32)}) 13. Re1 f5 14. exf5
Bxf5 15. Qe2 Qe8 16. f3 Qg6 17. Qg2 Bd3 18. b3 Rf7 19. Nce4 Nf6 20. Nf2 Bf5 $17
) 7... O-O {It is useful to compare this position with the Philidor defence.
One may argue that White has gained two tempi due to the forced retreat of the
black knight. At the same time, in the Philidor White rarely plays d4-d5. This
is a typical reaction in a position with ...Nbd7 and ... c7-c6 after Black
plays ...b7-b6, weakening the light squares.} 8. Re1 (8. a4 {is premature
since after} a5 {the knight could go to a6 and maybe to b4.}) (8. h3 c6 {
does not make much of a difference concerning the main line.}) 8... Nbd7 9. a4
c6 {We are getting closer to the Philidor patterns, with the difference
mentioned above: Black has not played ...b7-b6. Therefore, dxc6 is never a
threat and Black aims at playing ...Nb6 followed by an exchange on d5.} 10. a5
(10. Be3 Nb6 11. Bb3 cxd5 12. exd5 a5 $11) (10. Bf1 a5 $5 {followed by ...Nb6.}
) 10... b5 11. axb6 Nxb6 {Black has apparently spoiled the flexibility of his
structure, but also gained time for carrying out his plan.} 12. Bf1 (12. Bb3
cxd5 13. Nxd5 Nfxd5 14. Bxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Be6 16. Qd3 Qc7 17. b3 a5 $11) 12...
cxd5 13. Nxd5 Nfxd5 14. exd5 a5 $11 *

