17. Qb3 c6 18. Rad1 Ne6 $11) 10... Nc6 11. d4 (11. Nf1 Rfe8 12. Ng3 d5 13. Qb3
(13. exd5 Qxd5 14. Bg5 Rad8 $11) (13. Bg5 Rad8 14. Qb3 h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16.
Qxb7 Rb8 17. Qa6 Rxb2 $11) 13... Na5 14. Qc2 Nc6 15. Qb3 Na5 16. Qc2 $11 {
½-½ Schmitz,J (2319) -Jesse,I (2220) Germany 2009}) 11... Rfe8 {Black
continues developing, based on the fact that White has problems making
progress. The knight should stand on d2 to over-defend e4, which causes White
obvious developing problems.} 12. h3 {Just waiting.} (12. Nf1 {allows} exd4 13.
cxd4 d5 14. Ne5 dxe4 $11) (12. d5 {With the knight on d2, blocking the centre
is not promising.} Nb8 13. c4 c6 $132 {Black can continue with ...a7-a5, ...
Na6 followed by ...b7-b5 with or without the previous exchange on d5.}) (12. a3
Bd8 $5 {Clearing the e7-square for the knight and preparing the later bishop's
activation. It is not the only move, of course.} (12... a5 13. b3 $5) 13. b4
exd4 14. cxd4 Ne7 15. Bb2 Ng6 16. Qc2 c6 $11 {Black's play remains fluent. He
can combine play on both wings with, for instance, ...a7-a5 and ...Nh5. The
white knight remains stuck on d2.}) ({If you are curious why 12.h3 and 12.a3
are candidates, here is a possible answer:} 12. b3 exd4 $5 13. cxd4 Nb4 {
The b4-square} 14. Re2 (14. Re3 Ng4 {The g4-square} 15. Re2 f5 $132) 14... c5
15. d5 Nh5 $132) 12... a5 {Preparing to cause White problems with his
queenside development.} (12... exd4 {is also possible, even though it looks
like a premature concession. Play may transpose below, but can also have
independent value.} 13. cxd4 a5 $5 {The same idea as in the main line.} 14. d5
{One of the few moves having independent value.} Ne5 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Nc4 Bb4
17. Bd2 b5 18. Bxb4 axb4 19. Nd2 c6 20. dxc6 Qxc6 $11) 13. d5 (13. a3 a4 $11) (
13. b3 exd4 14. cxd4 a4 15. bxa4 Nb4 $11) (13. Rb1 exd4 $5 14. cxd4 Nb4 15. a3
Nd3 $11) 13... Nb8 14. c4 c6 15. Nf1 Na6 $11 *

