1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 d6 {Before moving on, we should keep in mind that
after} (3... Nf6 4. d3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 d6 {the main line is} 7. a4 {
not only gaining space, but also preparing the bishop's retreat to a2. Decades
ago, my friend Iulius Armas used this move as a surprise to defeat Michael
Adams. Nowadays, it is the most popular continuation.}) 4. O-O Be7 5. a4 {
With the obvious aim of transposing above.} Be6 {This is the best way of
keeping the game independent.} (5... Nf6 {is likely to transpose to the
aforementioned main line. Just to know, after} 6. d3 O-O 7. Re1 {the same idea
as in our main line is less restrictive:} Be6 {is usually answered with} 8.
Nbd2 {something White does not have in our line.}) 6. Bxe6 {White does not
have much of a choice now.} (6. d3 {leads to a structure facing Black with no
problems at all.} Bxc4 7. dxc4 a5 8. Nc3 b6 9. b3 Nf6 $11) 6... fxe6 {Black
has got double pawns in the centre, but this is not unusual in the Italian
game. Due to the tempo spent on a2-a4, White is a bit behind in development.}
7. d4 {Delaying this would allow Black to open the centre himself, when the
double pawns would suddenly prove strong.} (7. d3 Nf6 8. c3 a5 9. Qb3 Qd7 $5
10. Qxb7 (10. Ng5 d5 $11) 10... Rb8 11. Qa6 d5 {The queen has no retreats
available after Black has taken c4 under control. The minimum Black can count
on is a draw by perpetual attack against the queen with ...Rb6-b8. He could
also think of using his better development to prove his compensation.}) (7. c3
Nf6 8. Re1 d5 9. Qe2 $5 (9. d3 dxe4 10. dxe4 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nxe4 $13 12. Re1 Nc5
13. Nxe5 $2 Nxe5 14. Rxe5 Nb3 $19) (9. exd5 Qxd5 $15 {Black's double pawns
look even weaker now, but in fact it is White who faces some trouble due to
his delay in development and weakness on light squares. Black would most
likely castle long to increase his pressure along the d-file..}) (9. d4 Nxe4
10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 O-O $11) 9... dxe4 (9... Nxe4 10. d3 Nc5 11. b4 Nb3 12.
b5 Nca5 13. Nxe5 $14 Nxa1 $2 14. Qh5+ g6 15. Nxg6 $40) 10. Ng5 Qd5 11. b4 (11.
Nxe4 Na5 $5 12. Na3 O-O-O $15) 11... O-O 12. Nxe4 Rad8 $13 {Black's by far
superior development compensates for the pawn weaknesses.}) (7. a5 Nf6 8. a6 b6
9. Qe2 O-O 10. c3 d5 $11 11. exd5 $2 Qxd5 $15) 7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4
Nf6 (9... e5 $2 {is prematurely weakening the light squares.} 10. Qc4 Qd7 11.
Nc3 Nf6 12. Bg5 $16 {± Horvath,A (2488) -Boguszlavszkij,J (2173) Zalakaros
2020 (1-0, 53)}) 10. Nc3 {Taking d5 under control.} ({The immediate pawn break
} 10. e5 dxe5 11. Qxe5 {allows the active} Qd5 $1 12. Qxc7 (12. Qe2 O-O 13. Nc3
Qf5 $11) 12... Bd6 13. Qc3 O-O 14. Nd2 Ng4 15. Nf3 Rac8 16. Qd3 Qxd3 17. cxd3
Rc2 $44) 10... O-O 11. e5 {Otherwise, Black might consider either ...e6-e5 or .
.. d6-d5.} (11. Be3 d5 12. e5 c5 13. Qd1 (13. Qd2 Ng4 $15) 13... Ne8 $11) (11.
Rd1 Qe8 $5 {planning ...Qf7} 12. e5 Nd7 (12... dxe5 13. Qxe5 Bd6 14. Qe2 Qg6 {
planning ...Rf7 and ...Raf8 is also interesting.} 15. Qxe6+ Kh8 {Threatening
16...Bxh2!+ 17.Kxh2? Ng4+, winning the queen.} 16. h3 Rae8 17. Qc4 Nh5 $132) (
12... c5 $5 13. Qf4 {otherwise ...dxe5.} Nd5 14. Qg4 Qf7 15. Ne4 dxe5 $13) 13.
exd6 cxd6 14. Be3 Ne5 15. Nb5 Qg6 16. Kh1 Rac8 17. Nxd6 Bxd6 18. Qxd6 Nc4 19.
Qd4 Nxe3 20. Qxe3 Rxc2 $132) 11... dxe5 12. Qxe5 Qd6 {The second best square
for the queen, since d5 is not available already. White has the better
structure, but Black's superior development yields him good compensation for
the minor strategic problem.} 13. Qe2 (13. Re1 {Van Haren,M-Vreedenborg,C 
(2023) Maastricht 2007 (0-1, 33)} Qxe5 14. Rxe5 Kf7 15. Re2 Rad8 16. Bf4 Rd7
17. Rae1 Nd5 18. Bd2 (18. Be5 Bb4 $11) 18... Nb4 19. Bc1 Nc6 20. Rxe6 Nd4 21.
R6e4 Nxc2 $11) 13... Qc6 $5 {Preparing ...Bc5 and maintaining control over the
light squares.} (13... c6 $2 14. Re1 Rf7 15. Qxe6 Qxe6 16. Rxe6 Ng4 17. f3 Bc5+
18. Kf1 Nxh2+ 19. Ke2 Raf8 20. Be3 $18 {Mastrokoukos,G (2333) -Mastoras,I 
(2248) Aghia Pelagia 2004 (1-0, 37)}) (13... Rad8 $5 14. Re1 Nd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd5
$11) 14. Re1 (14. a5 Bc5 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Nd5 17. Nxd5 exd5 $11) (14. Be3
Nd5 $11 15. Bd2 (15. Bd4 Nf4 16. Qg4 Rf7 17. Rae1 h5 18. Qg3 Bh4 $1 19. Qf3
Qxf3 20. gxf3 Bf6 $15) 15... Bf6 $11) 14... Bc5 15. Be3 (15. Qxe6+ Qxe6 16.
Rxe6 Ng4 17. Ne4 Bd4 18. c3 Rae8 19. Rxe8 Rxe8 20. cxd4 Rxe4 21. Bd2 Rxd4 22.
Bc3 Rd7 $11) 15... Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Nd5 17. Qxe6+ Qxe6 18. Rxe6 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Rfe8
{Due to his queenside weaknesses, White cannot enjoy his extra pawn.} 20. Rae1
Rxe6 21. Rxe6 Rd8 22. Kf1 Kf7 23. Re4 Rd1+ 24. Ke2 Ra1 $11 *

